{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"3c6324ea-db4a-44f6-8ccb-aeba7053decc","content":"On macOS, when a process crashes the OS automatically generates a **`.ips` crash report**. You can find it in:\n\n1. **`~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/`** — for user-launched apps\n2. **`/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/`** — for system-wide crashes\n\nLook for a file named like `YourAppName_YYYY-MM-DD-HHMMSS_machinename.ips`.\n\nYou can also open **Console.app → Crash Reports** to browse them in a GUI.\n\n### Quick terminal command:\n```bash\nls -lt ~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/*.ips | head -5\n```\n\n### Notes\n- macOS does **not** produce Linux-style core dumps by default. The `.ips` file contains the full native backtrace, register state, and loaded binary info.\n- If you need to **symbolicate** the .NET runtime frames in the `.ips` file, you can use tools that download debug symbols from the Microsoft symbol server and run `atos` against them.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"bc9d8650-63eb-4ee1-b9a8-df566d519636","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about finding crash dumps/reports for a NativeAOT .NET app that crashed on macOS, without `createdump` available.","outputTokens":308,"requestId":"D808:29B0F9:9279EC:A96823:69FBEFE0"},"id":"cfbb858b-6926-4582-85c2-193cfa219836","timestamp":"2026-05-07T01:50:32.623Z","parentId":"0552333f-564c-4305-91ad-61cd1a78c1c4"}
